Have you tried using [`slice`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/slice)? It will return a shallow copy of a portion of an array into a new array object selected from the start to end index.

For example:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const fruits = [&quot;Banana&quot;, &quot;Orange&quot;, &quot;Apple&quot;, &quot;Mango&quot;];
    console.log(fruits.slice(1, 3)) // logs: [&quot;Orange&quot;, &quot;Apple&quot;]

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

You could use a [`filter`][1] to select the range of items that you want, where the second parameter is the index.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const fruits = [&quot;Banana&quot;, &quot;Orange&quot;, &quot;Apple&quot;, &quot;Mango&quot;];

    const getRange = (arr, start, end) =&gt; arr.filter((itm, idx) =&gt; idx &gt;= start &amp;&amp; idx &lt;= end)

    console.log(getRange(fruits, 2, 3))
    console.log(getRange(fruits, 0, 2))

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/filter

