You can use coroutines.

Using `compile &#39;org.jetbrains.kotlinx:kotlinx-coroutines-play-services:1.3.1&#39;`.

Your code will look something like this. (I wasn&#39;t sure what exceptions you wanted to catch or throw away, so I made educated guesses)

```kotlin
@Synchronized
private fun postOfferNow() {
    runBlocking {
        val storageRef = storge.reference
        val images = takenPicsPaths.map { image -&gt;
            async {
                val file = Uri.fromFile(File(image))
                val ref = storageRef.child(&quot;Images/$offerOwnerID/${file.lastPathSegment}&quot;)
                runCatching { ref.putFile(file).await() }
                  .map { ref.downloadUrl.await().toString() }
                  .getOrNull()
            }
        }.mapNonNull { it.await() }
        println(images)
    }
}

```

The `@Synchronized` annotation will only allow a single thread from you machine at a time from accessing the function which does not mean that the code following it will wait for the response of an _asynchronous call_ which in your case is `ref.putFile(file)` and hence `println` is returning an empty array. There are two methods to resolve this:   

**1).** Make a `println` call inside the `onSuccessListener` lambda or anything in general that has anything to do with the result of the _async_ call should be written inside the listeners.
 
```kotlin
@Synchronized
    private fun postOfferNow() {
        val storageRef = storge.reference
        val images = ArrayList&lt;String&gt;()
        for (image in this. takenPicsPaths) {
            val file = Uri.fromFile(File(image))
            val ref = storageRef.child(&quot;Images/$offerOwnerID/${file.lastPathSegment}&quot;)
            ref.putFile(file).addOnFailureListener {

            }.addOnSuccessListener {
                ref.downloadUrl.addOnCompleteListener {
                    val url = it.result
                    images.add(url.toString()) //here is where I add items to images
                    println(images)  // this would work
                }
            }
        }
        
    }
``` 
 
**2).** If you are familiar with _coroutines_ then use _async/await_
```kotlin
launch(Dispatchers.IO) {
    async {
    val response = await ref.putFile(file)
  }
}
```
Basically putting everything inside an _async_ block and using _await_ before every _async call_. You can learn more [here][1].  

But I would highly discourage the latter method while dealing with **Firebase**, you should totally rely on the _listeners_ provided by them.


  [1]: https://kotlinlang.org/docs/reference/coroutines/composing-suspending-functions.html#async-style-functions

