The problem is that `Object.keys` returns `string[]`. So as you map over those keys, each value (`id`) is type `string`. This type is more general than your specific keys of only `&quot;a&quot; | &quot;b&quot; | &quot;c&quot;` since `&quot;d&quot;` and every other possible string value is possible which is not valid props to the `SampleComponent` component. 

You can explicitly say `id` is of type `Key` to resolve this issue.

You could do something along these lines:

```typescript
export const obj = {
  a: 1,
  b: 2,
  c: 3
};

type Key = keyof typeof obj;

interface Props {
  id: Key;
}

const SampleComponent: React.FC&lt;Props&gt; = ({ id }) =&gt; &lt;h1&gt;{id}&lt;/h1&gt;;

const SampleComponentTwo: React.FC = () =&gt; (
  &lt;React.Fragment&gt;
    {Object.keys(obj).map((id: Key) =&gt; (
      &lt;SampleComponent id={id} key={id} /&gt;
    ))}
  &lt;/React.Fragment&gt;
);
```

